item.title: Introduction and Understanding the Data
item.description:
An overview of the project and motivations.

We decided to analyze the dataset from the trees of the city of Melbourne. We thought it would be interesting because it is something that is very easily overlook. When walking into a park or down the street people tend not to appreciate the green. Those trees are the equivalent of a natural cooling system.

What is the total size of your data? (MB, number of rows, number of variables, etc.

The size of the dataset is 14.8 Mb Urban_forest_in_Mebourne. There are 74.6K rows, each row representing a tree and 19 columns. The columns we decided to use in our analysis are mostly the’Common Name' of the tree, the ‘Family’ that the tree belongs to , the’Diameter Breast Height', the ‘Date Planted’ and the ‘Located in’ for the machine learning.

What are other properties? (What is the date range? Is is it geo-data?, then a quick plot of locations, etc.)

There is geo-data in the dataset (‘Latitude’, ‘Longitude’) that we are planning to use for heat-map representation. We are also going to incorporate the ‘Life Expectancy’ column so that the life expectancy is exceeded, the tree will disappear from the map.

The data has shape of 74579 rows and 19 columns . The columns of the data are: Index([‘CoM ID’, ‘Common Name’, ‘Scientific Name’, ‘Genus’, ‘Family’, ‘Diameter Breast Height’, ‘Year Planted’, ‘Date Planted’, ‘Age Description’, ‘Useful Life Expectency’, ‘Useful Life Expectency Value’, ‘Precinct’, ‘Located in’, ‘UploadDate’, ‘CoordinateLocation’, ‘Latitude’, ‘Longitude’, ‘Easting’, ‘Northing’], dtype=‘object’). item.title: Distribution of the Trees
item.description:
Fundamental distributions of the data.

To have an insight of the data and vizualize the basic distributions of them, we asked ourselves a sequence of questions we wanted to answer.

Yearly patterns

Most trees were planted during the year 1998, with years 2000 and 1997 following.

Monthly patterns

It can be seen that most trees are planted from October to January. This make perfect sense since, in the Southern hemisphere, those months are the meteorolgical period of spring and summer.

Monthly patterns for different families

We wanted to know if Is there any correlation between the months and different families of trees.

The dataset includes 61 different families of trees. We got the 14 most frequent families and tried to detect which month is prefered to plant trees that belong in a certain family.
